04061nam a22005175i 9780300188929DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20132013ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001889297 a10.12987/97803001889292doi  a(DE-B1597)486314  a(OCoLC)822890104  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a211/.70921 aJacoby, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great Agnostic :bRobert Ingersoll and American Freethought /cSusan Jacoby. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI The Making of an Iconoclast -- tII The Political Insider and the Religious Outsider -- tIII Champion of Science -- tIV The Humanistic Freethinker -- tV Church and State -- tVI Reason and Passion -- tVII Death and Afterlife -- tAfterword: A Letter to the "New" Atheists -- tAppendix A: Vivisection -- tAppendix B: Robert Ingersoll's Eulogy for Walt Whitman, March 30, 1892 -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the Gilded Age, which saw the dawn of America's enduring culture wars, Robert Green Ingersoll was known as "the Great Agnostic." The nation's most famous orator, he raised his voice on behalf of Enlightenment reason, secularism, and the separation of church and state with a vigor unmatched since America's revolutionary generation. When he died in 1899, even his religious enemies acknowledged that he might have aspired to the U.S. presidency had he been willing to mask his opposition to religion. To the question that retains its controversial power today-was the United States founded as a Christian nation?-Ingersoll answered an emphatic no.In this provocative biography, Susan Jacoby, the author of Freethinkers: A History of American Secularism, restores Ingersoll to his rightful place in an American intellectual tradition extending from Thomas Jefferson and Thomas Paine to the current generation of "new atheists." Jacoby illuminates the ways in which America's often-denigrated and forgotten secular history encompasses issues, ranging from women's rights to evolution, as potent and divisive today as they were in Ingersoll's time. Ingersoll emerges in this portrait as one of the indispensable public figures who keep an alternative version of history alive. He devoted his life to that greatest secular idea of all-liberty of conscience belonging to the religious and nonreligious alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFreethinkersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aFreethinkersxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxVerenigde Staten. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300188929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300188929.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles